Mr. Yvon Godin (Acadie-Bathurst, NDP):
Mr. Speaker, I am pleased to rise today to talk about an important subject that is dear to my heart. 
I will try to easy, since it is a question that is very dear to many hearts.  
The reason all of this is so dear to my heart goes back to the accident at the Westray Mine on May 9, 1922. 
We lost friends in this tragedy, 26 miners. 
Talking about this here in the House is a very emotional thing for me, because I myself am a former miner.  
I worked for more than 15 years in the depths of a mine, I remember that, in 1976, in the mine where I was working, we buried six miners in 18 months. 
It is really not easy to accept the death of a colleague in one's workplace.  
For example, one of those guys drove to work with me every day. 
One morning we came in together and by nighttime, he was gone.  
